"Abstract According to well placed government sources, the Clinton administration is mired in inter-departmental squabbles over its crypto and information warfare approaches. The first skirmish erupted on 3 December 1998 when Ambassador David Aaron, the US Undersecretary of Commerce for International Trade and President Clinton's Cryptography Special Envoy, announced that the 33-nation Wassenaar ‘Arrangement’ had agreed in Vienna, Austria to increase restrictions on the export of encryption software. Aaron reported that the Wassenaar signatories would tighten restrictions on cryptography exceeding 64 bits. According to one Commerce Department insider, Aaron's statement was made without the prior approval or knowledge of Vice President Gore. Aaron, according to the source, is increasingly acting as a ‘loose cannon’ on cryptography policy, a situation that is perturbing some Clinton administration officials."
